Almost the whole world is facing energy crisis at this time. It has become a challenge to meet the energy requirements due to the lack of natural gas and somewhere coal.
In India too, it is being said that the supply of coal is being reduced at many power plants. State governments have expressed concern about this and many power plants are facing shortage of coal.
Similarly, the supply of natural gas is also becoming a big challenge. While on one hand its supply is not sufficient, its demand is also increasing and the prices have increased.
image source, LIBERTY STEEL
Europe Of countries‚Äô problems
European countries are currently facing a big crisis of natural gas. These countries mostly depend on renewable energy, natural gas and nuclear power for their energy needs. Most of it is from natural gas.
However, at present the supply of natural gas in European countries is not in line with the demand. This demand is going to increase further in winter, which may hit the middle and low income groups the most.
The prices of natural gas are increasing continuously, the burden of which is bound to fall on the consumers.
Electricity prices are going to rise in the UK. According to a report, more than one million households in Britain will not be able to use electricity or other energy sources by the beginning of next year.
Last month, nine companies operating in this sector closed down. She could not bear the rising cost due to rising prices.
image source, Getty Images
Along with this, there is talk of removing the limit on prices so that companies can be saved from closure due to losses.
In Germany also power plants were closed and it is facing an energy crisis. Natural gas prices have increased in the US.
The energy needs of a country are met not only by keeping in mind the present but also the future. But, now suddenly the whole world is facing energy crisis. Production is low and prices are rising.
Experts do not consider any one reason responsible behind this, but many factors have together created these situations.
image source, Getty Images
increasing demand for natural gas
There has been an increase in the demand for energy around the world due to many reasons. Experts attribute this to the increasing demand for products and services in normal life after the corona epidemic, change in weather and reduction in coal production.
Economies came to a halt during the Corona pandemic. Both demand and production were low. The condition of the economies was deteriorating. But, when the impact of the epidemic subsided, countries gave economic reform packages to accelerate the economy.
In America, a trillion dollar economic package was given to improve the infrastructure, the effect of which was also seen on other industries. This spurred the construction and service industry and increased the demand for energy.
At the same time, change in weather has also been seen in many places. In many countries, the demand started increasing in the last winter itself.
